#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:5
msgid "Working with custom markers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:7
msgid "Here are some example using the :ref:`mark` mechanism."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:10
msgid "Marking test functions and selecting them for a run"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:12
msgid "You can \"mark\" a test function with custom metadata like this::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:14
msgid ""
"# content of test_server.py\n"
"\n"
"import pytest\n"
"@pytest.mark.webtest\n"
"def test_send_http():\n"
"    pass # perform some webtest test for your app\n"
"def test_something_quick():\n"
"    pass\n"
"def test_another():\n"
"    pass\n"
"class TestClass:\n"
"    def test_method(self):\n"
"        pass"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:30
msgid ""
"You can then restrict a test run to only run tests marked with ``webtest``::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:32
msgid ""
"$ py.test -v -m webtest\n"
"======= test session starts ========\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.5.1, pytest-2.9.2, py-1.4.31, pluggy-0.3.1 -- "
"$PYTHON_PREFIX/bin/python3.5\n"
"cachedir: .cache\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR, inifile:\n"
"collecting ... collected 4 items\n"
"\n"
"test_server.py::test_send_http PASSED\n"
"\n"
"======= 3 tests deselected by \"-m 'webtest'\" ========\n"
"======= 1 passed, 3 deselected in 0.12 seconds ========"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:44
msgid "Or the inverse, running all tests except the webtest ones::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:46
msgid ""
"$ py.test -v -m \"not webtest\"\n"
"======= test session starts ========\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.5.1, pytest-2.9.2, py-1.4.31, pluggy-0.3.1 -- "
"$PYTHON_PREFIX/bin/python3.5\n"
"cachedir: .cache\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR, inifile:\n"
"collecting ... collected 4 items\n"
"\n"
"test_server.py::test_something_quick PASSED\n"
"test_server.py::test_another PASSED\n"
"test_server.py::TestClass::test_method PASSED\n"
"\n"
"======= 1 tests deselected by \"-m 'not webtest'\" ========\n"
"======= 3 passed, 1 deselected in 0.12 seconds ========"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:61
msgid "Selecting tests based on their node ID"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:63
msgid ""
"You can provide one or more :ref:`node IDs <node-id>` as positional "
"arguments to select only specified tests. This makes it easy to select tests "
"based on their module, class, method, or function name::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:67
msgid ""
"$ py.test -v test_server.py::TestClass::test_method\n"
"======= test session starts ========\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.5.1, pytest-2.9.2, py-1.4.31, pluggy-0.3.1 -- "
"$PYTHON_PREFIX/bin/python3.5\n"
"cachedir: .cache\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR, inifile:\n"
"collecting ... collected 5 items\n"
"\n"
"test_server.py::TestClass::test_method PASSED\n"
"\n"
"======= 1 passed in 0.12 seconds ========"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:78
msgid "You can also select on the class::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:80
msgid ""
"$ py.test -v test_server.py::TestClass\n"
"======= test session starts ========\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.5.1, pytest-2.9.2, py-1.4.31, pluggy-0.3.1 -- "
"$PYTHON_PREFIX/bin/python3.5\n"
"cachedir: .cache\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR, inifile:\n"
"collecting ... collected 4 items\n"
"\n"
"test_server.py::TestClass::test_method PASSED\n"
"\n"
"======= 1 passed in 0.12 seconds ========"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:91
msgid "Or select multiple nodes::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:93
msgid ""
"$ py.test -v test_server.py::TestClass test_server.py::test_send_http\n"
"======= test session starts ========\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.5.1, pytest-2.9.2, py-1.4.31, pluggy-0.3.1 -- "
"$PYTHON_PREFIX/bin/python3.5\n"
"cachedir: .cache\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR, inifile:\n"
"collecting ... collected 8 items\n"
"\n"
"test_server.py::TestClass::test_method PASSED\n"
"test_server.py::test_send_http PASSED\n"
"\n"
"======= 2 passed in 0.12 seconds ========"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:109
msgid ""
"Node IDs are of the form ``module.py::class::method`` or ``module.py::"
"function``.  Node IDs control which tests are collected, so ``module.py::"
"class`` will select all test methods on the class.  Nodes are also created "
"for each parameter of a parametrized fixture or test, so selecting a "
"parametrized test must include the parameter value, e.g. ``module.py::"
"function[param]``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:117
msgid ""
"Node IDs for failing tests are displayed in the test summary info when "
"running py.test with the ``-rf`` option.  You can also construct Node IDs "
"from the output of ``py.test --collectonly``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:122
msgid "Using ``-k expr`` to select tests based on their name"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:126
msgid ""
"You can use the ``-k`` command line option to specify an expression which "
"implements a substring match on the test names instead of the exact match on "
"markers that ``-m`` provides.  This makes it easy to select tests based on "
"their names::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:131
msgid ""
"$ py.test -v -k http  # running with the above defined example module\n"
"======= test session starts ========\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.5.1, pytest-2.9.2, py-1.4.31, pluggy-0.3.1 -- "
"$PYTHON_PREFIX/bin/python3.5\n"
"cachedir: .cache\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR, inifile:\n"
"collecting ... collected 4 items\n"
"\n"
"test_server.py::test_send_http PASSED\n"
"\n"
"======= 3 tests deselected by '-khttp' ========\n"
"======= 1 passed, 3 deselected in 0.12 seconds ========"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:143
msgid "And you can also run all tests except the ones that match the keyword::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:145
msgid ""
"$ py.test -k \"not send_http\" -v\n"
"======= test session starts ========\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.5.1, pytest-2.9.2, py-1.4.31, pluggy-0.3.1 -- "
"$PYTHON_PREFIX/bin/python3.5\n"
"cachedir: .cache\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR, inifile:\n"
"collecting ... collected 4 items\n"
"\n"
"test_server.py::test_something_quick PASSED\n"
"test_server.py::test_another PASSED\n"
"test_server.py::TestClass::test_method PASSED\n"
"\n"
"======= 1 tests deselected by '-knot send_http' ========\n"
"======= 3 passed, 1 deselected in 0.12 seconds ========"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:159
msgid "Or to select \"http\" and \"quick\" tests::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:161
msgid ""
"$ py.test -k \"http or quick\" -v\n"
"======= test session starts ========\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.5.1, pytest-2.9.2, py-1.4.31, pluggy-0.3.1 -- "
"$PYTHON_PREFIX/bin/python3.5\n"
"cachedir: .cache\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR, inifile:\n"
"collecting ... collected 4 items\n"
"\n"
"test_server.py::test_send_http PASSED\n"
"test_server.py::test_something_quick PASSED\n"
"\n"
"======= 2 tests deselected by '-khttp or quick' ========\n"
"======= 2 passed, 2 deselected in 0.12 seconds ========"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:176
msgid ""
"If you are using expressions such as \"X and Y\" then both X and Y need to "
"be simple non-keyword names.  For example, \"pass\" or \"from\" will result "
"in SyntaxErrors because \"-k\" evaluates the expression."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:180
msgid ""
"However, if the \"-k\" argument is a simple string, no such restrictions "
"apply.  Also \"-k 'not STRING'\" has no restrictions.  You can also specify "
"numbers like \"-k 1.3\" to match tests which are parametrized with the float "
"\"1.3\"."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:186
msgid "Registering markers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:192
msgid "Registering markers for your test suite is simple::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:194
msgid ""
"# content of pytest.ini\n"
"[pytest]\n"
"markers =\n"
"    webtest: mark a test as a webtest."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:199
msgid ""
"You can ask which markers exist for your test suite - the list includes our "
"just defined ``webtest`` markers::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:201
msgid ""
"$ py.test --markers\n"
"@pytest.mark.webtest: mark a test as a webtest.\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.skip(reason=None): skip the given test function with an "
"optional reason. Example: skip(reason=\"no way of currently testing this\") "
"skips the test.\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.skipif(condition): skip the given test function if "
"eval(condition) results in a True value.  Evaluation happens within the "
"module global context. Example: skipif('sys.platform == \"win32\"') skips "
"the test if we are on the win32 platform. see http://pytest.org/latest/"
"skipping.html\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.xfail(condition, reason=None, run=True, raises=None, "
"strict=False): mark the the test function as an expected failure if "
"eval(condition) has a True value. Optionally specify a reason for better "
"reporting and run=False if you don't even want to execute the test function. "
"If only specific exception(s) are expected, you can list them in raises, and "
"if the test fails in other ways, it will be reported as a true failure. See "
"http://pytest.org/latest/skipping.html\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.parametrize(argnames, argvalues): call a test function multiple "
"times passing in different arguments in turn. argvalues generally needs to "
"be a list of values if argnames specifies only one name or a list of tuples "
"of values if argnames specifies multiple names. Example: "
"@parametrize('arg1', [1,2]) would lead to two calls of the decorated test "
"function, one with arg1=1 and another with arg1=2.see http://pytest.org/"
"latest/parametrize.html for more info and examples.\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.usefixtures(fixturename1, fixturename2, ...): mark tests as "
"needing all of the specified fixtures. see http://pytest.org/latest/fixture."
"html#usefixtures\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.tryfirst: mark a hook implementation function such that the "
"plugin machinery will try to call it first/as early as possible.\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.trylast: mark a hook implementation function such that the "
"plugin machinery will try to call it last/as late as possible."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:219
msgid ""
"For an example on how to add and work with markers from a plugin, see :ref:"
"`adding a custom marker from a plugin`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:224
msgid "It is recommended to explicitly register markers so that:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:226
msgid "there is one place in your test suite defining your markers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:228
msgid "asking for existing markers via ``py.test --markers`` gives good output"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:230
msgid ""
"typos in function markers are treated as an error if you use the ``--"
"strict`` option. Future versions of ``pytest`` are probably going to start "
"treating non-registered markers as errors at some point."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:237
msgid "Marking whole classes or modules"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:239
msgid ""
"You may use ``pytest.mark`` decorators with classes to apply markers to all "
"of its test methods::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:242
msgid ""
"# content of test_mark_classlevel.py\n"
"import pytest\n"
"@pytest.mark.webtest\n"
"class TestClass:\n"
"    def test_startup(self):\n"
"        pass\n"
"    def test_startup_and_more(self):\n"
"        pass"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:251
msgid ""
"This is equivalent to directly applying the decorator to the two test "
"functions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:254
msgid ""
"To remain backward-compatible with Python 2.4 you can also set a "
"``pytestmark`` attribute on a TestClass like this::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:257
msgid ""
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"class TestClass:\n"
"    pytestmark = pytest.mark.webtest"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:262
msgid "or if you need to use multiple markers you can use a list::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:264
msgid ""
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"class TestClass:\n"
"    pytestmark = [pytest.mark.webtest, pytest.mark.slowtest]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:269
msgid "You can also set a module level marker::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:271
msgid ""
"import pytest\n"
"pytestmark = pytest.mark.webtest"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:274
msgid ""
"in which case it will be applied to all functions and methods defined in the "
"module."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:280
msgid "Marking individual tests when using parametrize"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:282
msgid ""
"When using parametrize, applying a mark will make it apply to each "
"individual test. However it is also possible to apply a marker to an "
"individual test instance::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:286
msgid ""
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.foo\n"
"@pytest.mark.parametrize((\"n\", \"expected\"), [\n"
"    (1, 2),\n"
"    pytest.mark.bar((1, 3)),\n"
"    (2, 3),\n"
"])\n"
"def test_increment(n, expected):\n"
"     assert n + 1 == expected"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:297
msgid ""
"In this example the mark \"foo\" will apply to each of the three tests, "
"whereas the \"bar\" mark is only applied to the second test. Skip and xfail "
"marks can also be applied in this way, see :ref:`skip/xfail with "
"parametrize`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:303
msgid ""
"If the data you are parametrizing happen to be single callables, you need to "
"be careful when marking these items. `pytest.mark.xfail(my_func)` won't work "
"because it's also the signature of a function being decorated. To resolve "
"this ambiguity, you need to pass a reason argument: `pytest.mark."
"xfail(func_bar, reason=\"Issue#7\")`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:313
msgid "Custom marker and command line option to control test runs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:317
msgid ""
"Plugins can provide custom markers and implement specific behaviour based on "
"it. This is a self-contained example which adds a command line option and a "
"parametrized test function marker to run tests specifies via named "
"environments::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:322
msgid ""
"# content of conftest.py\n"
"\n"
"import pytest\n"
"def pytest_addoption(parser):\n"
"    parser.addoption(\"-E\", action=\"store\", metavar=\"NAME\",\n"
"        help=\"only run tests matching the environment NAME.\")\n"
"\n"
"def pytest_configure(config):\n"
"    # register an additional marker\n"
"    config.addinivalue_line(\"markers\",\n"
"        \"env(name): mark test to run only on named environment\")\n"
"\n"
"def pytest_runtest_setup(item):\n"
"    envmarker = item.get_marker(\"env\")\n"
"    if envmarker is not None:\n"
"        envname = envmarker.args[0]\n"
"        if envname != item.config.getoption(\"-E\"):\n"
"            pytest.skip(\"test requires env %r\" % envname)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:341
msgid "A test file using this local plugin::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:343
msgid ""
"# content of test_someenv.py\n"
"\n"
"import pytest\n"
"@pytest.mark.env(\"stage1\")\n"
"def test_basic_db_operation():\n"
"    pass"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:350
msgid ""
"and an example invocations specifying a different environment than what the "
"test needs::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:353
msgid ""
"$ py.test -E stage2\n"
"======= test session starts ========\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.5.1, pytest-2.9.2, py-1.4.31, pluggy-0.3.1\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR, inifile:\n"
"collected 1 items\n"
"\n"
"test_someenv.py s\n"
"\n"
"======= 1 skipped in 0.12 seconds ========"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:363
msgid "and here is one that specifies exactly the environment needed::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:365
msgid ""
"$ py.test -E stage1\n"
"======= test session starts ========\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.5.1, pytest-2.9.2, py-1.4.31, pluggy-0.3.1\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR, inifile:\n"
"collected 1 items\n"
"\n"
"test_someenv.py .\n"
"\n"
"======= 1 passed in 0.12 seconds ========"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:375
msgid "The ``--markers`` option always gives you a list of available markers::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:377
msgid ""
"$ py.test --markers\n"
"@pytest.mark.env(name): mark test to run only on named environment\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.skip(reason=None): skip the given test function with an "
"optional reason. Example: skip(reason=\"no way of currently testing this\") "
"skips the test.\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.skipif(condition): skip the given test function if "
"eval(condition) results in a True value.  Evaluation happens within the "
"module global context. Example: skipif('sys.platform == \"win32\"') skips "
"the test if we are on the win32 platform. see http://pytest.org/latest/"
"skipping.html\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.xfail(condition, reason=None, run=True, raises=None, "
"strict=False): mark the the test function as an expected failure if "
"eval(condition) has a True value. Optionally specify a reason for better "
"reporting and run=False if you don't even want to execute the test function. "
"If only specific exception(s) are expected, you can list them in raises, and "
"if the test fails in other ways, it will be reported as a true failure. See "
"http://pytest.org/latest/skipping.html\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.parametrize(argnames, argvalues): call a test function multiple "
"times passing in different arguments in turn. argvalues generally needs to "
"be a list of values if argnames specifies only one name or a list of tuples "
"of values if argnames specifies multiple names. Example: "
"@parametrize('arg1', [1,2]) would lead to two calls of the decorated test "
"function, one with arg1=1 and another with arg1=2.see http://pytest.org/"
"latest/parametrize.html for more info and examples.\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.usefixtures(fixturename1, fixturename2, ...): mark tests as "
"needing all of the specified fixtures. see http://pytest.org/latest/fixture."
"html#usefixtures\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.tryfirst: mark a hook implementation function such that the "
"plugin machinery will try to call it first/as early as possible.\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.trylast: mark a hook implementation function such that the "
"plugin machinery will try to call it last/as late as possible."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:396
msgid "Reading markers which were set from multiple places"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:402
msgid ""
"If you are heavily using markers in your test suite you may encounter the "
"case where a marker is applied several times to a test function.  From "
"plugin code you can read over all such settings.  Example::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:405
msgid ""
"# content of test_mark_three_times.py\n"
"import pytest\n"
"pytestmark = pytest.mark.glob(\"module\", x=1)\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.glob(\"class\", x=2)\n"
"class TestClass:\n"
"    @pytest.mark.glob(\"function\", x=3)\n"
"    def test_something(self):\n"
"        pass"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:415
msgid ""
"Here we have the marker \"glob\" applied three times to the same test "
"function.  From a conftest file we can read it like this::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:418
msgid ""
"# content of conftest.py\n"
"import sys\n"
"\n"
"def pytest_runtest_setup(item):\n"
"    g = item.get_marker(\"glob\")\n"
"    if g is not None:\n"
"        for info in g:\n"
"            print (\"glob args=%s kwargs=%s\" %(info.args, info.kwargs))\n"
"            sys.stdout.flush()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:428
msgid "Let's run this without capturing output and see what we get::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:430
msgid ""
"$ py.test -q -s\n"
"glob args=('function',) kwargs={'x': 3}\n"
"glob args=('class',) kwargs={'x': 2}\n"
"glob args=('module',) kwargs={'x': 1}\n"
".\n"
"1 passed in 0.12 seconds"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:438
msgid "marking platform specific tests with pytest"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:442
msgid ""
"Consider you have a test suite which marks tests for particular platforms, "
"namely ``pytest.mark.darwin``, ``pytest.mark.win32`` etc. and you also have "
"tests that run on all platforms and have no specific marker.  If you now "
"want to have a way to only run the tests for your particular platform, you "
"could use the following plugin::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:448
msgid ""
"# content of conftest.py\n"
"#\n"
"import sys\n"
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"ALL = set(\"darwin linux2 win32\".split())\n"
"\n"
"def pytest_runtest_setup(item):\n"
"    if isinstance(item, item.Function):\n"
"        plat = sys.platform\n"
"        if not item.get_marker(plat):\n"
"            if ALL.intersection(item.keywords):\n"
"                pytest.skip(\"cannot run on platform %s\" %(plat))"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:462
msgid ""
"then tests will be skipped if they were specified for a different platform. "
"Let's do a little test file to show how this looks like::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:465
msgid ""
"# content of test_plat.py\n"
"\n"
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.darwin\n"
"def test_if_apple_is_evil():\n"
"    pass\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.linux2\n"
"def test_if_linux_works():\n"
"    pass\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.win32\n"
"def test_if_win32_crashes():\n"
"    pass\n"
"\n"
"def test_runs_everywhere():\n"
"    pass"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:484
msgid "then you will see two test skipped and two executed tests as expected::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:486
msgid ""
"$ py.test -rs # this option reports skip reasons\n"
"======= test session starts ========\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.5.1, pytest-2.9.2, py-1.4.31, pluggy-0.3.1\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR, inifile:\n"
"collected 4 items\n"
"\n"
"test_plat.py sss.\n"
"======= short test summary info ========\n"
"SKIP [3] $REGENDOC_TMPDIR/conftest.py:12: cannot run on platform linux\n"
"\n"
"======= 1 passed, 3 skipped in 0.12 seconds ========"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:498
msgid ""
"Note that if you specify a platform via the marker-command line option like "
"this::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:500
msgid ""
"$ py.test -m linux2\n"
"======= test session starts ========\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.5.1, pytest-2.9.2, py-1.4.31, pluggy-0.3.1\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR, inifile:\n"
"collected 4 items\n"
"\n"
"test_plat.py s\n"
"\n"
"======= 3 tests deselected by \"-m 'linux2'\" ========\n"
"======= 1 skipped, 3 deselected in 0.12 seconds ========"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:511
msgid ""
"then the unmarked-tests will not be run.  It is thus a way to restrict the "
"run to the specific tests."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:514
msgid "Automatically adding markers based on test names"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:518
msgid ""
"If you a test suite where test function names indicate a certain type of "
"test, you can implement a hook that automatically defines markers so that "
"you can use the ``-m`` option with it. Let's look at this test module::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:523
msgid ""
"# content of test_module.py\n"
"\n"
"def test_interface_simple():\n"
"    assert 0\n"
"\n"
"def test_interface_complex():\n"
"    assert 0\n"
"\n"
"def test_event_simple():\n"
"    assert 0\n"
"\n"
"def test_something_else():\n"
"    assert 0"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:537
msgid ""
"We want to dynamically define two markers and can do it in a ``conftest.py`` "
"plugin::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:540
msgid ""
"# content of conftest.py\n"
"\n"
"import pytest\n"
"def pytest_collection_modifyitems(items):\n"
"    for item in items:\n"
"        if \"interface\" in item.nodeid:\n"
"            item.add_marker(pytest.mark.interface)\n"
"        elif \"event\" in item.nodeid:\n"
"            item.add_marker(pytest.mark.event)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:550
msgid "We can now use the ``-m option`` to select one set::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:552
msgid ""
"$ py.test -m interface --tb=short\n"
"======= test session starts ========\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.5.1, pytest-2.9.2, py-1.4.31, pluggy-0.3.1\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR, inifile:\n"
"collected 4 items\n"
"\n"
"test_module.py FF\n"
"\n"
"======= FAILURES ========\n"
"_______ test_interface_simple ________\n"
"test_module.py:3: in test_interface_simple\n"
"    assert 0\n"
"E   assert 0\n"
"_______ test_interface_complex ________\n"
"test_module.py:6: in test_interface_complex\n"
"    assert 0\n"
"E   assert 0\n"
"======= 2 tests deselected by \"-m 'interface'\" ========\n"
"======= 2 failed, 2 deselected in 0.12 seconds ========"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:572
msgid "or to select both \"event\" and \"interface\" tests::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:574
msgid ""
"$ py.test -m \"interface or event\" --tb=short\n"
"======= test session starts ========\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.5.1, pytest-2.9.2, py-1.4.31, pluggy-0.3.1\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR, inifile:\n"
"collected 4 items\n"
"\n"
"test_module.py FFF\n"
"\n"
"======= FAILURES ========\n"
"_______ test_interface_simple ________\n"
"test_module.py:3: in test_interface_simple\n"
"    assert 0\n"
"E   assert 0\n"
"_______ test_interface_complex ________\n"
"test_module.py:6: in test_interface_complex\n"
"    assert 0\n"
"E   assert 0\n"
"_______ test_event_simple ________\n"
"test_module.py:9: in test_event_simple\n"
"    assert 0\n"
"E   assert 0\n"
"======= 1 tests deselected by \"-m 'interface or event'\" ========\n"
"======= 3 failed, 1 deselected in 0.12 seconds ========"
msgstr ""
